Sure, here's a summary of the 10 criteria according to which a place can become a World Heritage Site:

1. A place can be designated as a World Heritage Site if it represents a masterpiece of human creative genius, reflecting artistic, scientific, or technical achievements.
2. It can also be designated if it exhibits an important interchange of human values, over a span of time or within a cultural area of the world, on developments in architecture, technology, monumental arts, town-planning, or landscape design.
3. The place must bear a unique or at least exceptional testimony to a cultural tradition or to a civilization which is living or which has disappeared.
4. It should be an outstanding example of a type of building, architectural or technological ensemble or landscape which illustrates significant stages in human history.
5. A place can also be designated if it is an outstanding example of a traditional human settlement, land-use, or sea-use which is representative of a culture or cultures, or human interaction with the environment, especially when it has become vulnerable under the impact of irreversible change.
6. The place must also meet at least one of the following six selection criteria: (vi) to be directly or tangibly associated with events or living traditions, with ideas, or with beliefs, with artistic and literary works of outstanding universal significance.
7. It should represent a masterpiece of creative genius; (vii) to be outstanding examples of a type of building, architectural or technological ensemble or landscape which illustrates (a) significant stage(s) in human history;
8. The place must be an outstanding example of a traditional human settlement, land-use, or sea-use which is representative of a culture or cultures, or human interaction with the environment;
9. It should be directly or tangibly associated with a living tradition or beliefs of a community or groups of communities;
10. Lastly, the place must be an outstanding example of a type of building, architectural or technological ensemble or landscape which illustrates (a) significant stage(s) in human history; (ix) to be outstanding examples of on-going ecological and biological processes in the evolution and development of terrestrial, fresh water, coastal and marine ecosystems and communities of plants and animals;
11. It should contain superlative natural phenomena or areas of exceptional natural beauty and aesthetic importance;
12. The place must be outstanding examples representing major stages of earth's history, including the record of life, significant on-going geological processes in the development of landforms, or significant geomorphic or physiographic features;
13. It should be outstanding examples representing significant on-going ecological and biological processes in the evolution and development of terrestrial, fresh water, coastal and marine ecosystems and communities of plants and animals;
14. Lastly, the place must contain the most important and significant natural habitats for in-situ conservation of biological diversity, including those containing threatened species of outstanding universal value from the point of view of science or conservation.
